author: Irishexaminer.com (digitaldesk@irishexaminer.com)
title: Letters to the Editor: Solidarity with the people of Palestine
text:
Last Saturday, more than 700 people marched through Cork City in support of the beleaguered Palestinian people. Organised by the Cork Palestine Solidarity Campaign this was the 39th weekly march since Israel began its horrifying bombardment and invasion of Gaza. It is an incredible display of indefatigable solidarity and human empathy from the extraordinary people of Cork.
Back in 2003 and 2004, as chairperson of the Cork Anti-War Campaign, I was involved in organising several large marches in Cork against the US war on Iraq. People still talk about the huge numbers that came out at that time, including a reported 100,000 at one anti-war march in Dublin in February 2003. Thousands also attended anti-war marches at Shannon airport.
These were indeed impressive demonstrations, but are nothing like the relentless and huge anti-war mobilisations that we have seen across Ireland and internationally over the past nine months in reaction to the ongoing Gaza massacre. There have been several massive national demonstrations in Dublin — and there will be another on July 20.
Certainly, the 39 consecutive marches in Cork — sometimes involving hundreds of people, sometimes thousands — will forever be a landmark in the history of anti-war activism in that city. And they continue.
Limerick has a similar weekly march. Moreover, solidarity vigils, pickets, marches, and other gatherings are happening every week across Ireland in villages, towns and cities from Baltimore to Belfast.
Co Cork alone has events regularly in towns such as Midleton, Mallow, Skibbereen, Baltimore, Clonakilty, Bantry, Bandon, and Cobh.
The depth and breadth of feeling in Ireland is clear. But is the Irish Government listening?
People are demanding more than words and symbolic gestures, welcome as these may be. The Government here surely must understand at this late stage that Israel will respond only to purposeful sanctions. Why has Ireland not yet, for example, enacted the Occupied Territories Bill?
It should do so immediately and also continue to push for a formal review of the EU-Israel Association Agreement. Israel is a rogue state that routinely breaches international humanitarian law and should be treated as such.
The horror in Gaza cannot be allowed to continue.
While there are many highly commendable government-funded organisations to encourage a more productive life for Irish pensioners they fail to highlight the poor facilities for the elderly in our hospital system.
The elderly are more likely to end up as long-stay patients in wards. They are put into geriatric wards which are full of clutter with very few, if any, areas where they can walk safely along corridors without all sort of obstacles in their way or have an area where they can speak with their loved ones with privacy.
Their charts are stuck on window sills, radiators, and anywhere convenient outside patients’ rooms.
Recently I heard of a case where a vulnerable woman patient was in a four-bed ward with three men. This was deemed unacceptable to mature women I have spoken with. They say this practice of mixed wards has been going on for years.
So what is the point of “age friendly” organisations if they do not demand that the elderly at their most vulnerable stage of life should be treated with the dignity they deserve rather than be treated like old motor cars ready for the junk yard.
This is not a complaint about medical staff who do their best in a system and in facilities which does not take the dignity of elderly into consideration.
Recently I was trawling through some excellent coverage online from Oireachtas TV.
In one clip, Micheál Martin was invited to the Seanad, in his capacity as defence minister, to communicate with and respond to the senators’ queries.
The particular questions related to pending Defence Forces’ legislation by the Government, and the questions were directed at the defence minister, mainly by Senator Gerard Craughwell, an Independent senator, who is a former and distinguished member of the Defence Forces, having also served in the British Army, and also as an educator, served as president of the Teachers Union of Ireland.
I quote from an early riposte by Mr Martin to a question by Mr Craughwell: “The hostility to the department [of Defence] that comes across, worries me.”
This was nothing more than another cheap shot, an intimidatory attempt to undermine the value and credibility of the senator’s status, who is also very capably supported by Cathal Berry TD on defence and other matters, being a former deputy commander of the Defence Forces elite ranger wing, in the Dáil.
We in the rapidly disintegrating ‘Defence Forces family’ need more than insults and intimidation from the minister.
I note that even the newly-elected Taoiseach got in on the offensive act recently, when demanding higher standards from the members of the Defence Forces, than other members of society... and yet he pays us less than any other state employees.
Get a grip, Simon.
Never mind the Ariane 6 — how about more buses and trains? Forget about space until we improve life on Earth. Pure daft.
As a Waterfordian who arrived to live in East Cork many years ago, I was delighted at the result of the All-Ireland hurling semi-final last Sunday, as the vast majority of our family were born in the Rebel County and are ardent Cork supporters (in all kinds of sports, actually).
The two unlikely contenders for All-Ireland glory in this years final, on Sunday, July 21, in Croke Park, would have been rank outsiders at the beginning of the championship.
Indeed, this Cork team, having ‘scraped through’ the round-robin series by a solitary point (losing games to Waterford and Clare) were given little chance of reaching the Senior All-Ireland final. However, this writer said to some of his friends after that narrow success: “If I was a betting-man I’d put a tenner on Cork to win the Liam McCarthy Cup this year (2024, for the 21st time).”
My dear departed Dad — having followed the Deise hurlers all his life (and was disappointed at great Waterford teams falling many times at the final hurdle) — used to tell me: “Apart from the skill required in the fastest ball game in the world, a large degree of good luck is also a necessity for a team to have on their side.”
Let’s hope that type of luck remains with Cork’s Senior hurlers for two more weeks ... at least.
Mary Henderson opines that Donald Trump is not fit to run for the position of “dog catcher much less commander in chief” — ‘Kamala Harris should take over from Biden’ (Irish Examiner, Letters, June 6). Really?
Dog catching is a highly skilled profession requiring agility, intelligence, empathy, powers of prediction, and an emollient persona.
A collection of the latest sports news, reports and analysis from Cork.

author: Ashitha Shivaprasad
title: Gold takes heart from rate cut expectations
text:
Markets Gold takes heart from rate cut expectations Tension in the Middle East and ceasefire negotiations lift bullion’s safe-haven appeal 06 May 2024 - 07:21 by Ashitha Shivaprasad Support our award-winning journalism. The Premium package (digital only) is R30 for the first month and thereafter you pay R129 p/m now ad-free for all subscribers. Subscribe now Picture: UNSPLASH
Bengaluru — Gold prices ticked higher on Monday, as the expectation that the Federal Reserve will start cutting interest rates later in the year and tension in the Middle East lifted bullion’s appeal.
Spot gold rose 0.3% to $2,309.24/oz by 4.27am GMT. US gold futures gained 0.5% to $2,318.80/oz.
“Investors will look at the political situation in the Middle East and how the ongoing negotiations for a ceasefire play out. If the hopes of a truce become lesser, gold will gain,” said Kelvin Wong, a senior market analyst for Asia Pacific at Oanda.
Prospects for a Gaza ceasefire appeared slim on Sunday as Hamas reiterated its demand for an end to the war in exchange for the freeing of hostages, and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu flatly ruled that out.
“Weaker US data offers more policy flexibility for the Fed in terms of rate cuts,” paving way for gold prices to stabilise, said IG market strategist Yeap Jun Rong.
Data on Friday showed that US job growth slowed more than expected in April, reinforcing expectations that the Fed will start cutting rates later this year.
Markets are pricing in a 67% chance of a US rate cut in September, as per CME’s FedWatch Tool. Lower interest rates reduce the opportunity cost of holding bullion.
New York Fed Bank president John Williams said on Friday that the 2% target for inflation is “critical” to the Fed’s efforts to achieve price stability, while Austan Goolsbee, president of the Chicago Fed, noted that the US rate-path “dot plot” needs more context.
Meanwhile, the Perth Mint’s gold product sales in April jumped two-fold from a month earlier, while silver sales fell to their lowest since December.
Among other precious metals, spot silver was up 1.3% to $26.89/oz. Platinum lost nearly 0.7% to $948.97 and palladium inched up 0.1% to $946.58.

title: Eolico in Sardegna: Scontro tra Governo e Regione
text: [ ](/a/AB907611-4E32-4596-98F1-03842793E429/Eolico-in-Sardegna-si-accende-lo-scontro-Confindustria-col-governo-Avanti) [Leggi](https://www.corriere.it/cronache/24_agosto_08/sardegna-si-accende-lo-scontro-sull-eolico-confindustria-col-governo-avanti-83a68092-2d34-48af-aa5a-afd361501xlk.shtml) La questione delle pale eoliche e della transizione ecologica in Sardegna ha acceso un acceso dibattito politico. Confindustria, attraverso l'associazione Elettricità Futura, si è schierata con il governo, sollecitando la Commissione Europea ad aprire una procedura d’infrazione contro la Regione Sardegna. Il consiglio dei ministri ha deciso di impugnare la legge sarda che prevede una moratoria di 18 mesi per gli impianti di produzione e accumulo di energia elettrica da fonti rinnovabili ancora non avviati. Secondo il ministro Pichetto Fratin, la legge approvata dal consiglio regionale della Sardegna "non è applicabile". Come previsto, il Governo Meloni ha impugnato la moratoria davanti alla Corte costituzionale. La legge regionale blocca per 18 mesi la realizzazione di nuovi impianti di produzione e accumulo di energia elettrica da fonti rinnovabili, una decisione che il governo ritiene inaccettabile. Nel frattempo, in diversi paesi della Sardegna, tra cui San Gavino Monreale e Monserrato, la cittadinanza sta raccogliendo firme per la proposta di legge di iniziativa popolare "Pratobello '24". Questa proposta mira a regolamentare l’installazione di impianti fotovoltaici e eolici a terra, garantendo che i progetti di energia rinnovabile rispettino e valorizzino il territorio sardo. La battaglia tra il governo e la Regione Sardegna sulla moratoria delle rinnovabili è solo all'inizio. Mentre il governo cerca di accelerare la transizione ecologica, la Regione e i cittadini sardi chiedono che questa avvenga nel rispetto delle bellezze naturali e delle caratteristiche uniche del territorio.

author: Andrea Gale
title: These Luxe Italian Shoes Look So Effing Chic — & They Can Withstand Any Winter Weather
text:
Style
These Luxe Italian Shoes Look So Effing Chic — & They Can Withstand Any Winter Weather
Go ahead, wear them to every holiday party.
Few things can frustrate outfit planning like wet weather — you want a shoe that perfectly coordinates with your look, but that won’t get ruined when the raindrops, sleet, and snow begin to fall. Such problems cease to exist with the Italian brand
Aquatalia, a luxe label that creates on-trend shoes especially designed to withstand moisture. Aquatalia crafts its shoes from leather treated with the brand’s proprietary weatherproofing technology that repels moisture and resists salt and stains while preserving the softness and suppleness of the leather, for shoes that will last season after season.
I sifted through the pairs that feature weather-ready craftsmanship in styles that you’ll be itching to wear ASAP, like a pair of slingbacks in the season’s latest metallics that can take you from work to your holiday party, or a pair of on-trend crystal embellished ballet flats — and a surprising, sophisticated take on the classic ankle boot in ivory leather with a snipped toe. Keep scrolling to find shoes that are sure to become your new favorites, no matter what the forecast has in store.
An On-Trend Pair Of Slingbacks In The Season’s Must-Have Metallic
When there’s no time for an outfit change between work and your holiday party, reach for the weatherproof
Arabella heel. A flared, lacquered kitten heel and elasticized slingback ensure the shoe is comfortable enough for all-day wear, while the snipped toe, decorative square buckle, and shimmery silver metallic leather effortlessly take your look from day to night. Also available in raspberry — a cheery, holiday red shade just as party-appropriate, along with a variety of chic neutrals — this shoe is primed to become your latest party essential.
Sizes: 5 — 12 | Colors: 5
These Versatile Heeled Booties
Trousers, denim, skirts, dresses — the mixed suede and leather
Rowanna boot will look incredible with so many pieces in your wardrobe, they’re sure to become a mainstay. Crafted from soft, weatherproof leather (this white shade is a mod choice) with a rubber outsole and inner zipper, they’re as practical as they are chic. They feature a snipped toe, fitted 6.8-inch shaft and slender 2.5-inch heel for a silhouette that can take you from day to night — and even that upcoming holiday party.
Sizes: 5 — 12 | Colors: 2
This Pair Of Pumps With A High Block Heel
If you can’t imagine a heel that’s stylish enough to pair with party outfits and actually comfy enough to dance the night away, Aquatalia’s
Peony shoe can expand your horizons. The slip-on weatherproof leather silhouette is designed with a 2.9-inch block heel and Aquatalia’s signature flexible outsole, for a shoe that’s just as much about function as it is about form. This on-trend metallic silver adds the perfect holiday pop.
Sizes: 5 — 12 | Colors: 11
A Pair Of Sleek, Classic Flats
From the dainty pointed toe to the luminous gold sheen of the leather, Aquatalia’s
Penina flats are full of chic details — how adorable would they be paired with a holiday mini dress? Featuring a covered 0.8-inch heel with a flexible rubber outsole, the weatherproof Penina is a part of Aquatalia’s 24/7 Collection; the sort of chic, wearable shoe you’ll want to wear constantly.
Sizes: 5 — 12 | Colors: 11
A Timeless Loafer With The Coziest Faux Fur Lining
Lined in the softest faux fur, the
Romy flat combines the sensation of your favorite cozy slippers with the the timeless silhouette of a loafer for a shoe that you’ll want to wear any time the temps turn chilly. The fuzzy lining is complemented by a sleek and subtle square toe and stacked sliver heel. Try pairing these weatherproof winter flats with slouchy trousers and a cashmere sweater for the ultimate in quiet luxury.
Sizes: 5—12 | Colors: 4
A Pair Of Over-The-Knee Boots To Wear With Skirts & Dresses
Try pairing the extended, over-the knee shaft of the
Natessa boot with skirts and dresses. The extra-long 18-inch shaft height will disappear under maxi and midi dresses, keeping the silhouette seamless and balanced. Featuring an inside zipper and a stacked 1-inch heel with a rubber outsole and leather sock lining, the shaft is designed with a hint of stretch for the ultimate in both comfort and timeless style. Made in Italy with a weatherproof build, these are boots that will go the distance.
Sizes: 5 — 12 | Colors: 3
These Suede Chukka Boots With A Fuzzy Lining
A pair of suede chukka boots like the
Madelina can pair with everything from dresses and skirts to loungewear — and come with the added benefit of a soft faux fur lining to protect against the cold. The lace-up design features a 1-inch heel with a slightly chunky EVA outsole, and a shaft height of nearly 5 inches. You’ll wear these practical yet adorable boots all winter long, because they’re inclement weather-ready.
Sizes: 5 — 12 | Colors: 3
These Tall Boots For Dressing Up & Staying Warm
Dress up and stay warm in these
tall heeled boots. The 15.5-inch shaft is crafted from stretch suede (that’s fully weatherproof) with an inner zipper for easy on and off. Try contrasting the fitted silhouette with flowy midi and maxi dresses. The sturdy 3.3-inch stacked heel and low-profile platform make these a polished choice for office and evening wear alike.
Sizes: 5 — 12 | Colors: 5
A Pair Of The Sweetest Slingback Flats
Day or night, any time is the right time for the
Janetta slingback flats. The elasticized strap and ground-level heel are comfy enough for all-day wear, while a pointed toe is accented by a square buckle for a little chic, evening-appropriate detail. Try pairing this black suede version with holiday velvets, or choose the metallic silver shade for a jolt of luminosity. True to form, these are constructed with Aquatalia’s weatherproof technology.
Sizes: 5 — 12 | Colors: 3
These Desk-To-Dance Floor Heels
The accessorizing potential of these weatherproof
Pasha heel cannot be overstated: The gleaming metallic leather, 1.8-inch heel, and pointed toe are laidback yet elegant, and would look just as incredible with denim and a T-shirt as a formal party dress. A flexible rubber outsole ensures good traction with ease of movement, whether that movement be to your desk or the dance floor.
Sizes: 5 — 12 | Colors: 12
This Pair Of Ankle Strap Suede Heels
You might not consider these
open-toed sandals holiday party material, but think again: The plush black suede, buckled ankle, and wide toe strap are more than substantial enough to pair with the heavier fabrics and deeper shades that are typical of the season — especially when paired with coordinating tights. A wide 1.5-inch block heel and rubber sole provide comfort, stability, and day-to-night versatility.
Sizes: 5 — 12 | Colors: 2
